# <type>(<scope>): <subject in imperative mood, ≤72 chars>
#
# Conventional Commits 1.0.0 — https://www.conventionalcommits.org
#   types : feat fix docs style refactor perf test build ci chore revert
#   scope : crate name without the mrmr- prefix (core, app, cli, grpc, …)
#           or a layer name (workspace, ci, deps, docs, hardware)
#   bang  : append ! after type/scope for breaking changes (e.g. feat(proto)!: …)
#
# Subject rules:
#   · imperative mood ("add", not "added" or "adds")
#   · no trailing period
#   · ≤72 chars including type/scope/punctuation
#   · capitalize first word of subject content
#
# ─── Body (what & why) ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# What problem does this solve? What changes about user-visible or
# system-visible behavior? The diff already shows what code moved; the
# body should explain why it had to.
#



# ─── Considered & rejected ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# What alternatives did you weigh? Why is this the right call? This is the
# single highest-value section in any commit body — future-you and future
# reviewers rediscover what you considered far more often than what you did.
#



# ─── Refs ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Refs: #<issue>, RFC NNNN, ADR-NNNN
# Closes: #<issue>            (only when this commit fully closes it)
# Breaking: <terse description of the break, surfaced in CHANGELOG>
#



# ─── Reminders ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# · Lines starting with '#' are stripped before commit.
# · Keep body lines ≤72 chars; long URLs may exceed.
# · `Signed-off-by:` is added automatically by `git commit -s`.
#   This repo has `format.signoff = true` configured, so just `git commit`.
# · Your private journal lives at $MRMR_JOURNAL (default:
#   .git/COMMIT_JOURNAL.md). It is never committed. Distill, don't paste.
